Exactly — that’s very close to how modern embodied AI and robotics research thinks about it.

The key idea is that movement and perception aren’t separate systems; they become tightly coupled.

A robot (or animal) builds useful internal representations partly by linking:

input → prediction → action → result → error → update

For example:

1. Camera sees object.
2. System predicts: “if I reach this way, I should touch it.”
3. Motor action happens.
4. Sensors report what actually occurred.
5. Difference between prediction and reality updates the model.

Over time, repeated pairings create increasingly useful internal structure — not just “what the world looks like,” but:

* “What changes when I act.”
* “Which signals matter.”
* “What tends to happen next.”
* “How my body affects my environment.”

Developmental robotics and embodied cognition research lean heavily into this idea. Infants do versions of this too — kicking legs, grabbing objects, dropping things repeatedly. They’re not only learning objects; they’re learning relationships between sensing, acting, and consequences.

This also connects to your coordination/compression thinking:

raw signals → paired experiences → reusable patterns → compressed skills → richer world model

The body becomes part of the learning system, not just a tool attached to it.